'''Barbara Aronstein Black''' (born 1933<ref name=AAAS />) is an American legal scholar. She was the first woman to head an [[Ivy League]] [[law school]].<ref>{{Cite news |first=Carol |last=Kleiman |title=More women practice law, but barriers remain |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/24878188.html?dids=24878188:24878188&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Mar+09%2C+1987&author=Carol+Kleiman&pub=Chicago+Tribune+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&desc=MORE+WOMEN+PRACTICE+LAW%2C+BUT+BARRIERS+REMAIN&pqatl=google |date=March 9, 1987 |publisher=Chicago Tribune }}</ref> when she became Dean of [[Columbia Law School]] in 1986.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Winning due credit for life experience |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=NGkaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XCoEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5320,4607595&dq=barbara-aronstein-black+columbia&hl=en |publisher=Milwaukee Journal |date=January 6, 1986 }}</ref> Black is George Wellwood Murray Professor of Legal History at Columbia.<ref name="Nyt"/>
Black received her B.A. from [[Brooklyn College]] in 1953,<ref>{{Cite news |title=Challenge rules, roles, new graduates told |first=Michael |last=Moss |date=6 June 1988 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/104001740.html?dids=104001740:104001740&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jun+06%2C+1988&author=By+Michael+Moss&pub=Newsday+%28Combined+editions%29&desc=Challenge+Rules%2C+Roles%2C+New+Graduates+Told&pqatl=google |publisher=Newsday }}</ref> her LL.B. from [[Columbia Law School]] in 1955, and a Ph.D. from [[Yale University]] in 1975.<ref name="cls">{{Cite web |url=http://www.law.columbia.edu/law_school/communications/reports/winter2003/b_black |title=Faculty Profiles - Barbara Aronstein Black |publisher=Columbia Law School }}</ref> Black was elected a Fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] in 1989.<ref name=AAAS>{{cite web|title=Book of Members, 1780–2010: Chapter B|url=http://www.amacad.org/publications/BookofMembers/ChapterB.pdf|publisher=American Academy of Arts and Sciences|accessdate=July 26, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110725002054/http://www.amacad.org/publications/BookofMembers/ChapterB.pdf| archivedate= 25 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> She was also for two years president of the [[American Society for Legal History]].<ref name="cls"/> Black's work has been concentrated in the area of [[contracts]] and [[legal history]]. She is a recipient of the [[Elizabeth Blackwell Award]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hws.edu/about/blackwell.aspx |title=The Blackwell Award |publisher=Hobart and William Smith College }}</ref> and of the Federal Bar Association Prize of Columbia Law School.<ref>{{Cite web |title=HWS: Barbara Aronstein Black |url=http://www.hws.edu/about/blackwell/black.aspx |publisher=Hobart and William Smith College}}</ref>
Barbara Black is the widow of constitutional scholar and civil rights pioneer [[Charles Black (professor)|Charles Black]],<ref name="Nyt">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/05/08/nyregion/charles-l-black-jr-85-constitutional-law-expert-who-wrote-on-impeachment-dies.html|date=May 8, 2001 |title=Charles L. Black Jr., 85, constitutional law expert who wrote on impeachment, dies |publisher=New York Times |first=Robert |last=McFadde }}</ref> with whom she had three children.<ref>{{Cite journal |url=https://www.amazon.com/memories-Charles-Columbia-School-professor/dp/B0008ETJ6O |journal=Yale Law Journal |title=Some memories of Charles L. Black, Jr. |date=June 1, 2002}}</ref>
